She flipped through the blank pages, writing down the date on one of them. Then, below the date, she wrote: "5/11/648-12/13/648".
"Recalling past events?" Avery asked, looking at the old notebook. Carly nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's almost Christmas now."
Carly tapped twice on the lightsaber, indicating "no". Avery wasn't surprised. Ice King never allowed Carly to leave because in his eyes, she was "a flaw". Carly was born a mute, and she was the only girl in the family, while all the other children were boys.
Avery was also like that, in his own unique way. When Avery openly expressed his non-binary identity, the world seemed to change as well. As a punishment for being different, Avery was often assigned to work alone most of the time.
He was also forced to be a princess's servant. However, he didn't mind because he had a friend.
“Your birthday is coming up, isn't it?” Avery asked, remembering that it was the princess's birthday in a few days. Carly nodded, a faint sadness flashing in her shallow blue eyes.
“Do you want to celebrate?” Avery asked, recalling how Carly had answered this question last time.
Not wanting to. Carly tapped the table. Avery knew that this was a difficult topic for Carly to open up about. On this day, she was imprisoned in this room, while her mother was executed. Avery was an infant at the time, but he remembered the anger of the servants and the citizens. He had heard that Queen Elwynn was a good queen and that she could magically predict future events.
“So... what do you want to do?” Avery asked. Carly looked up at him, excited. She handed Avery a piece of paper. However, when he looked down at it...
6 inch x 6 inch canvas
White, shades of blue pigment
6 different-sized brushes
Easel
“You want me to find those things for you?” Avery turned to the silent princess, who was tapping repeatedly, her ponytail swaying back and forth. “Right?” When he saw this normally silent princess so enthusiastic about something unrelated to books, he couldn't help but laugh. This was the first time she wanted something outside of the room.
“Alright! See you later?” Avery said, standing up and walking through the scattered papers and notebooks.
Carly nodded and continued to burrow deeper into the thick blanket, recalling her memories.
She walked out of the room, feeling relieved that the princess was finally willing to try new things and even requested some things that were beyond her capability (such as paint).
She crossed the hall again, trying her best to ignore the whispers of the maids.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Elwynn, so she always goes to that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
“She looks like a man, is that normal?”
He couldn't take the words anymore, so he covered his ears. He went to the royal painter's room, which was located on the east wing, the second door on the left.
Avery arrived in front of that door, which looked just like Carly's door, beautifully decorated. There was a white dragon on the door, one of the six original dragons, said to be the one that created the Frost Kingdom. It wasn't surprising that the painter liked history and painted the white dragon on the door.
He opened the door, expecting everything to be the same as before. For example, paint, pencils, and paper were scattered all over the place, and easels blocked every inch of the wall. However, the scene in the room was completely different. The room was clean, and there was a red velvet background and a stool. The stool was occupied by Crown Prince Aquilo, who was painting a portrait.
“Ah, good morning, Avery! Want to see your future king's portrait?” Aquilo asked, winking at Avery.
“Sorry, Your Highness,” TA replied, starting to look around for the things Carly Princess wanted. “I’m just here to pick up some art supplies.”
“Little treasure, you’re leaving so soon?” Aquilo asked, “But I want to see you again!”
“I don’t want to,” Avery found the art supplies on the list and put them into a box. “And I’m not a girl anyway.”
The prince didn’t take it seriously. “Oh, baby, you know this is just a phase! When you grow up, it won’t be a problem!” He mumbled vaguely.
“I have to go,” TA said, feeling very uncomfortable because the prince was still chattering. TA remembered all the negative evaluations of TA’s gender identity from others. I really want to get away from him.
“So soon you’re leaving?” The prince suddenly appeared at the doorway, ignoring the royal painter's cries.
“That's not the behavior a future king should have!” Avery spoke loudly.
“No one will know. People won't believe you, and if that painter still cherishes his life, he won't say anything anyway.” The prince turned around to look at the painter, then leaned in close to Avery. “Do you think a date would be fun?” Avery shivered in fear. Of course, Avery had heard many threats before, but they were not from the prince, let alone this future king.
“You don't know what the word 'no' means?” Avery scolded, pushing the prince away.
“No.” Aquilo smiled and replied. This prince who could get whatever he wanted certainly didn't know what the word "no" meant.
Avery raised an eyebrow. “Why do you, of all people, want to go out with me? How many suitors do you have? Hundreds?”
He chuckled and interrupted, "To be exact, it's over five hundred." He shook his head, with his hair fluttering in the cold wind.
"See? Why do you have to choose me? I'm the plague of the palace." Avery hugged his arms.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo placed a finger on Avery's chin, forcing Avery to look up at him.
